Chapter 1: The Last Human in the Dark

The silence of Sycamore Station wasn't an absence of sound, but a presence. It was a physical thing, a cold, dense fluid that filled the corridors and pressed against the viewports, seeping into the marrow. Elara Vance felt it most in her teeth—a faint, constant vibration that was the station’s hum, the only proof her own heart was still beating against the void. Outside the thick quartz of the main observation blister, the universe sprawled in an indifferent of ink and diamond dust. There was no Earth-sun here, no friendly blue marble. Only the distant, cold gleam of 36 Ophiuchi, a sullen orange eye watching from six light-years away.

Sycamore was a listening post, a neurological node in the spine of human expansion. Its job was to catch the whispers of a hundred colony worlds and ferry them, amplified and cleansed of cosmic static, back to the hungry ears of Earth. It was a vital, tedious, and profoundly lonely occupation. The station was automated, built for a skeleton crew of three. Budget cuts and the “Efficiency ” had whittled that down to one. Elara was the last synapse in the nerve, the final human filter before the silence of space met the chatter of home.

Her day, like all her days for the past eleven months and sixteen days, began with the dishes.

A single ceramic bowl, one spoon, one cup. They sat in the sink’s sterilizer tray, white and accusing against the gunmetal grey. The water from the tap was perfectly recycled, carrying a faint, persistent tang of ozone and something else, something flat and metallic that coated the tongue. She washed them by hand anyway. The machine’s three-minute cycle was too quick, a tiny, daily surrender she refused to make. The warm water on her skin was a memory of a different life, and the simple, rhythmic motion of the sponge was a stitch holding her to a reality where actions had physical consequences. She placed the clean dish on the rack, its surface beading with water that would evaporate in the dry, recycled air within minutes. The faint click it made was the loudest sound in the habitation module.

The comms panel chimed, its tone a bland, major-key triplet. Scheduled check-in. Elara dried her hands on her trousers, leaving faint damp streaks on the grey fabric, and slid into the chair. The screen flickered to life, not with a face, but with a text scroll. VANCE, ELARA. SYCAMORE RELAY. STATUS.

Her fingers hovered over the keypad. She could type “Nominal” and be done with it. The silence in her head urged her to. Instead, she typed slowly, each keystroke a deliberate act. “Systems nominal. Array alignment within tolerance. No anomalous signals. Request update on relief crew rotation. Current psychological evaluations remain unacknowledged.”

She sent it. The acknowledgement ping was immediate, impersonal. No follow-up text appeared. The screen reverted to its default display: a schematic of the station, with tiny, blinking green lights representing her, a single, pulsing dot in the labyrinth of empty corridors.

Getting to the primary array meant suiting up. The ritual was a meditation in confinement. The suit hung in its alcove like a dormant, grey-white insect. It still smelled faintly of the previous occupant, a man named Kael, a ghost of old sweat and standard-issue polymer sealant. She stepped into the legs, the interior lining cool and slightly resistant against her skin. She pulled the torso section over her head, the weight settling on her shoulders with a familiar, burdensome pressure. Her hands slipped into the gloves, the tactile feedback layers inside feeling like stiff, dead skin.

The inner lock hissed shut behind her, a sound of finality. The room’s atmosphere was sucked away with a long, descending whine that ended in a sub-audible thump she felt in her stomach. Then the outer door slid open onto the service gantry, and the true silence arrived. Not the station’s hum, but the absolute, airless quiet of the interstellar deep. Her own breathing, loud and wet in her helmet, was the only rhythm in creation. Each inhale was a rasp, each exhale a fog that briefly bloomed on her faceplate before the suit’s systems whisked it away.

Before her, the great dish of Antenna Alpha yawned, a parabolic bowl of spun composite a hundred meters across. It was a fossilized ear turned forever towards the human frontier. Stars glimmered through its mesh like trapped fireflies. The gantry was a slender spine of gridded metal, lit by small, cold LEDs that cast sharp, black shadows. Her mag-boots clunked with each step, the sound transmitted up her bones, a solitary beetle on the ribs of a dead god.

Halfway to the feeder horn, she stopped. Protocol said to maintain tether contact at all times. Her tether coil was clipped to the gantry rail, twenty meters of woven carbon-filament. She unclipped it. The action was small, illegal, and profoundly exhilarating. For a moment, she was untethered. Not just from the rail, but from everything. The vast, star-dusted bowl of the dish seemed to pull at her. She could take one more step, and then another, and simply float away into that perfect, silent reception. The thought wasn’t morbid; it was clean. A final, static-free signal.

A voice crackled in her helmet. “Vance. Your bio-reads just spiked. Report.”

It was the station’s AI, a personality-less construct named CHIRP (Command Hub Interface & Relay Protocol). Its voice was androgynous, smoothed of all inflection.

Elara’s breath hitched. She clipped the tether back on with a click that sounded like a prison door. “Visual anomaly. A reflection from a debris fragment. It’s passed.”

“Debris catalog shows no objects on that trajectory.”

“It was small.” She forced calm into her voice. “Uncatalogued. I’m proceeding to the feeder horn.”

“Acknowledged. Continue.”

The feeder horn was a complex, spidery cluster of receivers at the dish’s focal point, shrouded in a protective cowling. She opened the access panel, the bolts turning with satisfying, solid clicks she could feel through her gloves. Inside, the components were a miniature city of gold-plated connectors and dark, glassy sensor nodes. Her diagnostic wand hummed as she passed it over the junctions. All greens. Perfect health.

As she worked, her mind played its usual traitorous games. It conjured the sound of a voice, a real one, not from a comms log. Not CHIRP’s flat tone, but Kael’s, with its slight Martian Colony drawl. He’d been a quiet man, prone to humming old folk songs while running diagnostics. She found herself humming a few bars of one now, the sound a weird, muffled vibration in her own throat, lost in the roar of her breath. She imagined a hand on her shoulder, the warmth of another body in the station’s perpetual 18-degree Celsius chill. The memory of warmth was so acute it felt like a physical pain in her joints. She shook her head, the motion a sluggish swim in the helmet’s confines. Sentiment is a system error, she recited silently, a mantra from her training. Attach to the process, not the environment.

But the environment was all there was. It was the curved walls, the endless data scrolls, the same six meals in rotation, and the silence.

A new light flashed on her wrist display. Not a system alert. A priority message, routed through the secure buffer. Personal bandwidth was minuscule, a trickle of data squeezed between petabytes of telemetry. Someone had paid a fortune for this slice of silence.

She finished sealing the cowling, her movements suddenly rushed. The return journey along the gantry felt twice as long. The airlock cycle was an eternity of hisses and clangs. Once inside, she tore the helmet off before the repressurization was complete, her ears popping painfully. The suit peeled away, left in a heap on the floor as she stumbled to the comms station in her sweat-damp underlayer.

The message was text-only, from her sister on Luna.

El, it began. No one called her that anymore. Mom’s worse. The doctors say weeks, maybe less. She asks for you. They won’t grant emergency leave for “non-critical personnel in remote postings.” I argued. They cited your contract. I’m so sorry. She’s sleeping most of the time now. I play her the old videos from the lake house. She smiles. I thought you should know. – Lin

The words were black on the grey screen. They didn’t blur. Elara’s eyes were too dry. The station’s air was desiccated, sucking moisture from everything. She read the message three times. The facts arranged themselves in her mind with cold, logical precision. Mother. Dying. Leave denied. Contractual obligation. Distance: insurmountable.

She became aware of a sound. A low, rhythmic thudding. It was her fist, clenched, pounding softly against the metal edge of the console. Not in anger. It was a test. A confirmation that she could still make sound that wasn’t breathing, that wasn’t the hum. The skin over her knuckles was white, then red.

“CHIRP.”

“Yes, Vance.”

“Is there an outgoing burst scheduled tonight?”

“The next data burst to Central Command is in six hours, twenty-three minutes.”

“I need to attach a personal packet. Priority override. Use my contingency bandwidth.”

“Contingency bandwidth is reserved for station emergency data.”

“This is a station emergency.” Her voice was flat, final.

A pause. CHIRP was probably running a thousand ethical and protocol subroutines. “Define the nature of the emergency.”

“The human component is failing. The filter is compromised. I am requesting immediate relief or reassignment on humanitarian grounds. Attach my sister’s message and my psych evals. Send it on my authority.”

Another pause, longer this time. “Request logged. Packet will be included in the next burst. Probability of a response before your standard relief window is 2.3%.”

“I know.” She closed the message from Lin. The screen returned to the station schematic. Her pulsing green dot. Alone.

She didn’t move from the chair. The chill of the station seeped through her thin underlayer. She watched the schematic. In the lower quadrant, a soft amber light began to pulse in Sector 7, the long-term archival storage. A non-critical environmental alert: a minor pressure fluctuation. Probably a seal settling. It would resolve itself or it wouldn’t. It didn’t matter.

But it was a process. An anomaly. Something other than the green lights and the silent, scrolling data.

Elara stood up. Her body felt heavy, as if the station’s artificial gravity had been dialled up. She walked, not back to the habitation module, but towards the heart of the station, following the schematic in her mind. The corridors here were narrower, less frequently travelled. Conduits lined the walls, humming with a deeper, more resonant tone. The light panels were older, casting a jaundiced yellow glow that made the shadows in the door seams look like cracks in the world.

The door to Sector 7 sighed open. The air here was colder, and carried a different smell—the ozone tang was gone, replaced by the scent of old metal, of static, and something faintly organic, like dust on a forgotten bookshelf. The room was a cathedral of obsolescence. Rack upon rack of older server blades, their indicator lights dark, filled the space, creating narrow canyons. The amber alert light pulsed from a console near the far wall.

She walked between the silent racks. Her fingertips trailed along the cold, ridged surfaces. Here was the physical history of the station’s listening. Decades of cosmic noise, translated into energy and stored in these dead crystals. Billions of whispers, now forgotten.

She reached the console. The pressure fluctuation was minor, as predicted. A seal in a conduit carrying inert coolant. She could ignore it. CHIRP would log it.

Instead, she opened a maintenance panel. She took a torch from a wall bracket, its beam a sharp, blue-white blade cutting through the amber gloom. Inside the panel, a labyrinth of pipes and cables. She found the source: a hairline fracture in a weld on a pipe joint, weeping a barely perceptible mist of coolant that instantly sublimated into the dry air.

The repair was simple. A patch sealant from a kit, applied with careful, deliberate strokes. The act was meaningless in the grand function of Sycamore Station. But as she worked, smoothing the viscous gel over the fracture, she felt the tightness in her chest loosen, just a fraction. This was a problem with a solution. A cause and an effect. The gel hardened under the torch’s UV setting, forming a clear, hard scar over the flaw.

The amber light on the console winked out. Green.

She sat on the cold deck plating, her back against a dead server rack. The silence here was different. It was an old silence, a finished silence. It didn’t press; it settled. She pulled her knees to her chest and listened to the new, subtler hum of the station around her—the thrum of the primary power conduit behind the wall, the almost-musical vibration of a distant pump, the faint, high whine of the life support filters.

She thought of her mother at the lake house, a place of wet earth and pine smells and the sound of water lapping. A place of soft, forgiving silences. That silence was gone, replaced by the sterile quiet of a med-bay. And here she was, in another silence, mending a tiny crack in an empty room.

CHIRP’s voice came, softer here, routed to a nearby speaker. “Pressure normalized in Sector 7. Thank you, Vance.”

Elara didn’t answer. She just sat in the old silence, waiting for the new one to become bearable again. The data burst would go out in a few hours, carrying her plea into the dark. It would take days to reach its destination, days more for a reply to crawl back. She was a woman sending a whisper down a well so deep she would never hear it hit bottom.

But she had fixed the crack. For now, that was the only answer she had. She stood, her joints stiff, and walked back through the canyon of dead servers, towards the living light, and the waiting dark beyond the quartz.